In Fig. 7, we examine the radial extent probed by each method. We plot ratios of the Hi velocities and radii relative to the halo values as a function of baryonic mass. Both spatially resolved methods (left and middle columns in Fig. 7) underpredict the maximum halo speed and corresponding radius by very similar factors at a given baryonic mass. With galaxies at M
 M, the H i size at the 1 M pc limit (R
) extends to the ‘flat’ part of the rotation curve. This is apparent with the velocity ratios being close to 1 above this mass. At lower masses, the H i size shrinks as galaxy mass decreases, and limits the radial extent of spatially resolved rotation curves. As the H i shrinks, it no longer extends to the radius where the halo’s maximum velocity is reached. This shrinking of H i size is the primary reason that the spatially resolved H i methods underpredict the maximum rotation speed of the lowest-mass galaxies.

Dwarf galaxies exhibit more non-circular orbits due to baryonic feedback. With more dispersion-supported galaxies in the lower mass range, the discrepancy between assuming the mass-enclosed potential (V
) versus the mid-plane gravitational potential (V
) becomes larger. This may explain the steeper bTFR slope for V
 () versus V
 (). Non-circular motions are discussed further in Section 4.2, and will be explored in a future work.

Like previous galaxy simulations with CDM (e.g. Ferrero et al. 2012; Sales et al. 2017), we predict a turndown in the bTFR when the true maximum rotation velocity of the halo is measured (black points; Fig. 6). The bTFR turndown occurs at M
M, or a corresponding rotation speed  km s. However, we determine the rotation velocity in other ways, including measuring within the outermost H i radius (at 1 M pc) using the mass enclosed in spherical shells (V
), the gravitational potential in the mid-plane of the galaxy (V), and various widths of the unresolved H i line profile (W
,W
,W
). We find that none of these more observationally oriented velocity measurements can recover the underlying turndown in the bTFR.
